Not sure about correctness / security, but I am currently using the following workaround:

```diff
diff --git a/vendor/github.com/containers/common/libnetwork/internal/rootlessnetns/netns_linux.go b/vendor/github.com/containers/common/libnetwork/internal/rootlessnetns/netns_linux.go
index 1531ee52e..61797a8c3 100644
--- a/vendor/github.com/containers/common/libnetwork/internal/rootlessnetns/netns_linux.go
+++ b/vendor/github.com/containers/common/libnetwork/internal/rootlessnetns/netns_linux.go
@@ -275,6 +275,11 @@ func mountAndMkdirDest(source string, target string, fstype string, flags uintpt
 func (n *Netns) setupMounts() error {
 	// Before we can run the given function,
 	// we have to set up all mounts correctly.
+	// Unless /run is writable already: this is possible if podman is running as
+	// root inside some other container with user namespaces
+	if unix.Access("/run", unix.W_OK) == nil && unix.Access("/var/lib/cni", unix.W_OK) == nil {
+		return nil
+	}

 	// The order of the mounts is IMPORTANT.
 	// The idea of the extra mount ns is to make /run and /var/lib/cni writeable
```

@rhatdan I don't believe it's related to pasta vs slirp4netns. Changing it back to slirp4netns ends up in the same error. It looks like the path to the netns (`/run/containers/storage/networks/rootless-netns/`) is passed in to rootlessnetns from the rest of podman.

There seems to be two issues here:

1. When podman is running as root inside another container, the netns path defaults to somewhere in `/run`, or at least the `ref-count` file is expected to be located in there. So once `/run` is overmounted during `setupMounts()`, all the files no longer exist;
2. When `rootlessnetns` creates its own mount namespace, it does not set the root of that namespace to be `MS_PRIVATE|MS_REC`. This results in mounts inside there to propagate outside (as `systemd-nspawn` mounts the container root as `MS_SHARED`), and causing `/run` outside of podman to be overmounted as well, breaking the system.
